{{Expand French|Géologie de la France|date=July 2016}}
[[File:France geological map-fr.svg|thumbnail|right|Geologic map of [[France]].]]
[[File:Domaines geologiques france.png|thumbnail|left|Divisions in French Regional Geology.]]
The regional '''geology of France''' is commonly divided into the [[Paris Basin]], the [[Armorican Massif]], the [[Massif Central (geology)|Massif Central]], the [[Aquitaine Basin]], the [[Pyrenees]], the [[Alps]], the [[Côte languedocienne]], the [[Sillon rhodanien]], the [[Massif des Vosges]], the [[Massif Ardennais]], the [[Alsace graben]] ([[Rhine graben]]) and Flanders Basin.<ref name="European and Asian regional geology">{{cite book|first=ed. by Eldridge M. Moores|title=Encyclopedia of European and Asian regional geology|year=1997|publisher=Chapman & Hall|location=London [u.a.]|isbn=978-0412740404}}</ref>

==Alpine orogen==
{{Main|Geology of the Alps}}
The regions [[Alsace]], [[Franche-Comté]], [[Rhône-Alpes]] and [[Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur]] are part of the [[Western Alps]].<ref name="Schmid 2004">{{cite journal|last=Schmid|first=Stefan M.|author2=Fügenschuh, Bernhard |author3=Kissling, Eduard |author4= Schuster, Ralf |title=Tectonic map and overall architecture of the Alpine orogen|journal=Eclogae Geologicae Helvetiae|date=30 April 2004|volume=97|issue=1|pages=93–117|doi=10.1007/s00015-004-1113-x}}</ref> Sediment from the [[Valais ocean]] crop out in the [[Versoyen unit]]. The basement of the [[Briançonnais zone|Briançonnais microcontinent]] crop out at [[Gran Paradiso]], [[Dora Maira]], [[Ambine]], [[Vanoise Massif|Vanoise]] and [[Ruitor]]. The Briançonnais cover sequences crop out in the [[Zone Houillère]]. External massifs include the [[Belledonne massif]], [[Mont Blanc massif]], [[Pelvoux-Écrins massif]] and the [[Argentera massif]]. Sediments from the [[Piemont-Liguria Ocean]] crop out in [[Embrunais]] and [[Ubaye]].<ref name=Bousquet_Tectonic_Alps>{{cite web|last=Bousquet|first=Romain|title=http://perso.univ-rennes1.fr/romain.bousquet/Alps/Maps/tecto.html|url=http://perso.univ-rennes1.fr/romain.bousquet/Alps/Maps/tecto.html|accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref> The [[Jura mountains]] are part of the [[Helvetic nappes]], that represent deposits from the European margin that were involved in the [[Alpine orogeny]].<ref name="Schmid 2004" />

==Massif central==
[[File:France Massif central.jpg|thumb|The Massif Central highlighted on an elevation map.]]
{{Main|Massif Central (geology)}}
The geographic region of the [[Massif Central]] coincides with the geologic region with the same name. It is part of the [[Variscan]] orogenic cycle.<ref name="Lardeaux 2001">{{cite journal|last=Lardeaux|first=J.M|author2=Ledru, P |author3=Daniel, I |author4= Duchene, S |title=The Variscan French Massif Central—a new addition to the ultra-high pressure metamorphic 'club': exhumation processes and geodynamic consequences|journal=Tectonophysics|date=28 February 2001|volume=332|issue=1–2|pages=143–167|doi=10.1016/S0040-1951(00)00253-5|url=http://patrick.ledru.info/pdf/Lardeaux%20et%20al.pdf|accessdate=28 February 2013}}</ref> It was also a region of active volcanism during the [[Cenozoic]].

