[[File:Gerlovo.jpg|right|thumb|View of Gerlovo at [[Tushovitsa]]]]
'''Gerlovo''' or '''Gerilovo''' ({{lang-bg|Герлово, Герилово}}) is a small geographic and ethnographic region in [[Northern Bulgaria|Northern]] [[Bulgaria]], a hilly fertile [[valley]] in the northeastern [[Balkan Mountains]], south of the [[Ludogorie]] region. It lies between the Lisa, Preslav-Dragoevo and Kotel-Varbitsa mountains and covers much of [[Varbitsa (town)|Varbitsa]] municipality of [[Shumen Province]], with smaller parts in [[Omurtag (town)|Omurtag]] municipality ([[Targovishte Province]]) and [[Kotel, Bulgaria|Kotel]] municipality ([[Sliven Province]]). The main river is the [[Kamchiya]], which runs through the entire valley and forms the [[Ticha Reservoir]]; the only sizable town is Varbitsa. Four strategically important [[mountain pass]]es run through the region: the [[Preslav Pass]], [[Dervent Pass]], [[Kotel Pass]] and [[Varbitsa Pass]].

The population mostly consists of [[Bulgarians]] and [[Turks in Bulgaria|Turks]];[http://promacedonia.org/ki/ki_priturka.htm] there is an [[Alians|Alian]] community. 

[[Gerlovo Beach]] on [[Ioannes Paulus II Peninsula]] in [[Livingston Island]], [[Antarctica]] is named after Gerlovo region.<ref>[http://data.aad.gov.au/aadc/gaz/scar/display_name.cfm?gaz_id=136860 Composite Gazetteer of Antarctica:] Gerlovo Beach.</ref>

